Raman and XPS were further applied to investigate the evolution of surface properties during the oxidative cleavage of GO (Fig. 2
                     ). As shown in Fig. 2a, the ID/IG value of GQDs was 1.2, which was much higher than that of GO (1.02). This indicated that O3/H2O2/ultrasound oxidation could increase the amount of defective basal planes for GQDs. More interestingly, the percentage of CO (286.7eV) and CO (287.3eV) surface groups decreased distinctly while that of COOH groups (288.5eV) increased with prolonging the reaction time, as shown in Fig. 2b–d and Table 1
                     . The evolution of surface functional groups was presumably attributed to the oxidative effect by O3/H2O2/ultrasound process.

The as-prepared GQDs were used to modify GCEs as electrochemical sensors for the detection of heavy metal ions (Fig. 6
                     ). For example, GQDs sensor exhibited excellent performance on the detection of Cu2+ (Fig. 7
                     ) with a low detection limit of 3×10−10
                     M (atN/S=3). The obtained linearity of DPASV signal verse Cu2+ concentration was as high as 0.995, which was quite superior to the pristine GO (Fig. S2). Despite of lower electrical conductivity of GQDs, both the microsize and surface properties make them highly promising for trace heavy metal ions detection. The microsize of GQDs endowed higher surface areas and more active sites for ions adsorption and redox reactions. Moreover, abundant COOH groups, which were easily converted into negatively charged −COO− in aqueous solution, had electrostatic attraction towards positively charged ions. Hence a superior efficiency of ions detection efficiency can be achieved on a GQDs-modified GCEs [31]. With a further heating treatment, the resultant GQDs exhibited improved electrical conductivity (Fig. S3) and fewer COOH groups. The DPASV gradients of the calibration curve slope are 6.946 and 3.478μAmg−1 for thermal-treated GQDs at 150 and 300°C for 1h, respectively, which are much lower than 94.32 obtained from as-generated GQDs (Fig. S2). This further indicated the COOH-enriched GQDs had great potentials and unique advantages in electrochemical detection of metal ions.
